. In-between Poppy and Rubber Fields. Experimenting a Transborder Livelihood among the Akha in the Northwestern Frontier of Laos -- t12. A Fortuitous Frontier Opportunity. Cardamom Livelihoods in the Sino-Vietnamese Borderlands -- tConclusion. Frictions in Trans-Himalayan Studies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe societies in the Himalayan borderlands have undergone wide-ranging transformations, as the territorial reconfiguration of modern nation-states since the mid-twentieth century and the presently increasing trans-Himalayan movements of people, goods, and capital reshape the livelihoods of communities, pulling them into global trends of modernization and regional discourses of national belonging. This book explores the changes to native senses of place, the conception of border - simultaneously as limitations and opportunities - and what the authors call "affective boundaries," "livelihood reconstruction," and "trans-Himalayan modernities." It addresses changing social, political, and environmental conditions that acknowledge growing external connectivity even as it emphasizes the importance of place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aTrans-Himalayan study, Zomia, modernity, livelihood reconstruction, migration, landscape transformation.1 aCederlöf, Gunnel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheng, Yang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiemberger, Hildegard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrew, Georgina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalipeau, Brendan A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela